# Superwork Workflow

## Overview

This project uses `.superwork/` as the local workflow and spec runtime.

## Package Map

{{ package_map }}

## Required Entry Points

1. Use `superwork-init` when `.superwork/` is missing or incomplete.
2. Use `superwork-start` at the beginning of every coding task.
3. Route design-heavy or unclear feature work to `superwork-brainstorming`.
4. Use `superwork-using-git-worktrees` before plan execution in isolated workspaces.
5. Use `superwork-writing-plans` after design approval.
6. Use `superwork-executing-plans` to execute written plans.
7. Route direct feature work to `superwork-tdd` when scope is already clear, and require it to save `.superwork/plans/*.md` before any RED or implementation work starts.
8. Route bug work to `superwork-debugging`.
9. Before `superwork-check`, make an explicit `superwork-code-simplifier` decision: run it after targeted verification is green when recently touched code needs behavior-preserving cleanup, or state why it is skipped.
10. Run `superwork-check` only after that `superwork-code-simplifier` decision is explicit.
11. Require `superwork-check` to make an explicit `superwork-update-spec` decision (`update/create/no-update`), and default to `no-update` when no durable rule or contract changed.

## Tooling Paths

- Context load: `superwork-start` (skill-internal tooling)
- Design artifacts: `.superwork/prd/*.md`
- Plan artifacts: `.superwork/plans/*.md`
- Spec check: `superwork-check` (skill-internal tooling)
- Spec update decision: `superwork-update-spec` (skill-internal tooling)
- Never generate or copy `scripts/*.py` into this project as runtime output.

## Default Verification Hints

- Prefer `{{ package_manager }}` commands when Node tooling is present.
- Use planning track for non-trivial feature scope: brainstorming -> worktrees -> writing-plans -> executing-plans.
- Even on the direct feature path, save `.superwork/plans/*.md` before the first RED test; chat-only or memory-only plans do not count.
- Use `superwork-code-simplifier` only after behavior is verified, never as a substitute for TDD or debugging.
- If `superwork-code-simplifier` is skipped, state why the current diff does not need behavior-preserving cleanup before `superwork-check`.
- Re-read the relevant spec indexes before implementation and before completion.
- Update specs only when new durable rules, contracts, edge cases, or test requirements appear.
